Realdus Columbus was ucceeded at Rome by Bartholomaeus Eutachius; a Man very knowing and curious in Anatomy, but extreamly devoted to Galen, as one may ee by this Paage; 
   t uno verbo me expediam, talem eum ee (c. Galenum) aeverem, qualem opinor neminem in poterum futurum, fuie nunquam plane confirmo. Quare dubiis in rebus dientire ab eo honete non poumus, ed magis expedire, decereque putandum est, illo Duce crrare, quàm his illive Magitris hodie erudiri, nè dicam cum iis vera entire 
Barthol. Eutachij Oium Examen, p. m. 189.. Too great a Partiality for o ingenious a Man. And it may be, this was one Reaon why Vealius o much endeavoured to leen Galen's Authority; becaue the Humour of the Age was uch, that nothing then was to be received, but what was to be met with in him. But certainly they are in the wrong, who, becaue Galen is mitaken in ome things, do now wholly reject him, and lay him aide as good for nothing. The wiet and mot experienced in the Art may read his Works, and in reading him, if jut and not prejudiced, will acknowledge, a Satisfaction and an Advantage they have received from him.

I hall only add, That the Servile Offices that thee Creatures are oberved to perform, might formerly, as it does to this very day, impoe upon Mankind to believe, that they were of the ame Species with themelves;
but that only out of ullennes or cunning, they think they will not peak, for fear of being made Slaves. Philotratus Philotratus in vita Apollonij Tyanaei, lib. 3. cap. 1. p. m. 110, & 111. tells us, That the Indians make ue of the Apes in gathering the Pepper; and for this Reaon they do defend and preerve them from the Lions, who are very greedy of preying upon them: And altho' he calls them Apes, yet he peaks of them as Men, and as if they were the Husbandmen of the Pepper Trees,
< in non-Latin alphabet > . And he calls them the People of Apes; < in non-Latin alphabet > . Dapper Dapper Decription de l' Afrique, p. m. 249. tells us, That the Indians take the Baris when young, and make them o tame, that they will do almot the work of a Slave; for they commonly go erect as Men do. They will beat Rice in a Mortar, carry Water in a Pitcher, &c. And Gaendus Gaendus in vita Pierskij, lib. 5. p. m. 169. in the Life of Pieresky, tells us, That they will play upon a Pipe or Cittern, or the like Muick, they will weep the Houe, turn the Spit, beat in a Mortar, and do other Offices in a Family. And Acota, as I find him quoted by Garcilao de la Vega Garcilao de la Vega Royal Commentaries of Peru, lib. 8. cap. 18. p. 1333. tells us of a Monkey he aw at the Governour's Houe at Cartagena, whom they ent often to the Tavern for Wine, with Money in one hand, and a Bottle in the other; and that when he came to the Tavern, he would not deliver his Money, until he had received his Wine. If the Boys met with him by the way, or made a houting or noie after him, he would et down his Bottle, and throw Stones at them; and having cleared the way, he would take up his Bottle, and haten home. And tho' he loved Wine exceively, yet he would not dare to touch it, unles his Mater gave him Licene. A great many Intances of this Nature might be given that are very urpriing. And in another place tells us, That the Natives think that they can peak, but will not, for fear of being made to work. And Bontius Jac. Bontij Hit. Nat. & Med. lib. 5. cap. 32. p. m. 85. mentions that the Javans had the ame Opinion concerning the Orang-Outang, Loqui verò eos, eaque Javani aiunt, ed non velle, ne ad labores cogerentur.
